For $n$ balls, $P(A_i) = \frac{1}{n}$, $P(A_i \cap A_j) = \frac{(n-2)!}{n!} = \frac{1}{n(n-1)}$, and so on. The number of terms in $\sum_{i<j} P(A_i \cap A_j)$ is $\binom{n}{2}$, in $\sum_{i<j<k} P(A_i \cap A_j \cap A_k)$ is $\binom{n}{3}$, and so forth.

