Solution: ## Step 1
To find $P\left(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup A_3\right)$, we can apply Theorem 1.1-6, which states that for any events $A$, $B$, and $C$, $P(A \cup B \cup C) = P(A) + P(B) + P(C) - P(A \cap B) - P(A \cap C) - P(B \cap C) + P(A \cap B \cap C)$.

## Step 2
Given that $P\left(A_i\right) = 1/3$ for $i = 1, 2, 3$, $P\left(A_i \cap A_j\right) = (1/3)^2$ for $i \neq j$, and $P\left(A_1 \cap A_2 \cap A_3\right) = (1/3)^3$, we can substitute these values into the formula.

## Step 3
Substituting the given probabilities into the formula: $P\left(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup A_3\right) = P(A_1) + P(A_2) + P(A_3) - P(A_1 \cap A_2) - P(A_1 \cap A_3) - P(A_2 \cap A_3) + P(A_1 \cap A_2 \cap A_3)$.

## Step 4
Calculate each term: $P(A_1) + P(A_2) + P(A_3) = 1/3 + 1/3 + 1/3 = 3 \times (1/3) = 1$.

## Step 5
